question:
Consider $A=\left( \begin{array}{rr}
1 & 1 \\ 
0 & 1 \end{array}
\right)$ and  $B=\left( \begin{array}{rr}
a & b \\ 
c & d \end{array}
\right)$. If $A$ commutes with $B$, (AB = BA) then which of the following statements is correct?

Let $A=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
-1 & 2 & 1 \\ 
7 & 1 & 0 \end{array}
\right)$,  $B=\left( \begin{array}{rr}
-1 & 1 \\ 
7 & 1 \\ 
2 & 0 \end{array}
\right),$ and $C=\left( \begin{array}{rr}
-1 & 2 \\ 
0 & 1 \end{array}
\right)$. Which of the following statements is correct?

Indicate which of the following is a linear combination of $A=\left[\begin{array}{rr}
      3& 2\\
			0 & 1 
    \end{array}\right]$, $B=\left[\begin{array}{rr}
      0& -1 \\
			1 & 2 
    \end{array}\right]$ and $C=\left[\begin{array}{rr}
      5& 4 \\
			-1 & 0
    \end{array}\right]$.

Suppose that $A=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}  
-2  & -1 & 1 \\ 
0 & 1 & 2\\
2  & 1 & -2\end{array}
\right)$, $B=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}  
4  & 1 & 0\end{array}
\right)$, and $C=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}  
0  & 3 & -1\end{array}
\right)$. Find $X$ if $X\cdot A-B=C$.

Find the rank of the matrix  $\left( \begin{array}{rrr}  
-1  & z & 2 \\ 
1 & -1 & 1\\
z  & -1 & 1\end{array}
\right)$, where $z$ is a real number.

Let $A=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
-1 & 2 & 0 \\ 
2 & -4 & 0 \end{array}
\right)$. Which of the following statements is correct?

Let  $A=\left( \begin{array}{rr}
1 & 3 \\ 
2 & -1 \end{array}
\right)$ and $f\left(x\right)=x^3-2x+5I_{2\times2}$. Find $f(A)$.

Indicate which of the following is a linear combination of $A=\left[\begin{array}{rr}
      3& 2\\
			0 & 1 
    \end{array}\right]$, $B=\left[\begin{array}{rr}
      0& -1 \\
			1 & 2 
    \end{array}\right]$ and $C=\left[\begin{array}{rr}
      5& 4 \\
			-1 & 0
    \end{array}\right]$.

Find ${\left(C^T \cdot B-6 \cdot I^{-1}\right)}^2$, where $B=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
2 & 1 & 1 \\ 
0 & 0 & 3 \end{array}
\right)$, $C=\left( \begin{array}{rrr}
3 & 3 & 1 \\ 
1 & -2 & 2 \end{array}
\right)$, and $I$  -- identity matrix.
